### D10. Config surface — opt-in, not default-on

Codex P1 caught that my earlier "default-on" was hostile to existing
users. ⌘⇧K is VS Code's `Delete Line` and JetBrains' `Push...`. A
silent upgrade that registers a system-wide shortcut while those apps
are focused would steal muscle memory without consent. Unacceptable.

**Revised policy**:

- **Fresh installs** (first run on a machine with no existing
  `~/.config/minutes/config.toml`): palette shortcut defaults to `true`
  AND the user sees a first-run notification "Minutes added a command
  palette — press ⌘⇧K to open it. Disable in Settings if needed."
- **Upgrades** (existing config.toml without a `[palette]` section):
  palette shortcut defaults to `false`. The next settings UI visit
  shows a pill "New: command palette — enable?" and the user opts in
  explicitly

**Implementation note**: `PaletteConfig::default()` returns
`shortcut_enabled: true` — this is what a fresh install loads. For
upgrades, detect by checking whether `config.toml` existed before
this load. Config loading already has this affordance (the load path
writes a default config if missing). The check is:

1. `config_path.exists()` before load → upgrade path
2. Otherwise → fresh install path

For the upgrade path, after loading, rewrite the config to include
`[palette] shortcut_enabled = false` explicitly, so the user's next
edit sees the option visibly.

**Alternative considered**: always default off. Rejected because fresh
installs deserve to see the feature without hunting in settings.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize)]
pub struct PaletteConfig {
    /// Whether the global palette shortcut is enabled.
    pub shortcut_enabled: bool,
    /// The palette shortcut string (e.g., "CmdOrCtrl+Shift+K").
    pub shortcut: String,
}

impl Default for PaletteConfig {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            shortcut_enabled: true,  // fresh install only
            shortcut: "CmdOrCtrl+Shift+K".into(),
        }
    }
}
```

Added as `palette: PaletteConfig` on `Config`. Upgrade path overrides
`shortcut_enabled` to `false` before save.

**Dogfood**: per codex P1, I must dogfood the hotkey with Finder, VS
Code, JetBrains, and Firefox focused before calling the default
"acceptable". The dev-app tests via `install-dev-app.sh` are the test
surface. Any real conflict observed during dogfood → rebind the default
to something cleaner like `CmdOrCtrl+Shift+O` or `CmdOrCtrl+Shift+Space`
before merge.

Registration: in `main.rs::setup()`, after `live_shortcut` registration,
following the same pattern — read config, register via
`app.global_shortcut().register(...)`, stash the shortcut string on
`AppState`. Handler branch: add `palette_shortcut_id` alongside
`live_shortcut_id` in the plugin handler at `main.rs:558` and route to
`commands::handle_palette_shortcut_event(app, event.state())`.

`handle_palette_shortcut_event` only reacts to `ShortcutState::Pressed`
(not Released) — the palette is a toggle on press, not a hold-to-talk.

## Risk table (adversarial, post-codex-pass-1)

| # | Risk | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| R1 | ⌘⇧K conflicts with VS Code `Delete Line`, JetBrains `Push...`, Firefox `Web Console`, Finder `Connect to Server` | Upgrade path defaults the shortcut to **off** (D10). Fresh install defaults to on but shows a first-run notice. Dogfood with all four apps focused before calling the default acceptable. If real conflicts, rebind to `CmdOrCtrl+Shift+O` |
| R2 | Palette window hits the Tauri v2 capability permission gotcha | Smoke test uses the EXACT production pairing: `app.emit_to("palette", ...)` + `currentWindow.listen(...)`. Ship only after both pairings demonstrated working. See D4 |
| R3 | TS fuzzy matcher is non-deterministic (float math) or drifts from user expectation | **Integer tuple comparator**, no floats (D2). ≥10 deterministic unit tests. Backend re-fetches on state events so visibility never drifts from truth |
| R4 | Visible list stale during recording / live / dictation state changes while palette is open | `currentWindow.listen` on `recording:start`, `recording:stop`, `live-transcript:state`, `dictation:state`, re-fetch via `palette_list` on each. Re-fetch again just before `palette_execute` and abort if the focused command left the visible set (D2 rule 3) |
| R5 | Recents file corruption bricks the palette | Parse failure → treat as empty + move corrupt file to `.broken` + log warning. Never fatal. Full unit test list in D5 |
| R6 | Recents silently eat data on downgrade (newer variant unknown to older client) | Parse entries as raw `serde_json::Value`, not `ActionId`. Unknown entries are hidden from UI but preserved byte-for-byte on write. Version-mismatch files are read-only (D5) |
| R7 | Preflight double-call has subtle races | Preflight is pure/read-only (verified in `capture.rs`). The double call is intentional; palette runs its own first to return a synchronous error, existing background path still runs its own. Documented in D6 |
| R8 | D6 over-claims what preflight covers | Honest framing in D6: preflight catches process + device + call routing only. Disk, mic permission, and PID failure still happen later. Release notes do not promise "all silent failures fixed" |
| R9 | Window lifecycle race on fast ⌘⇧K mashing | Explicit `Closed/Opening/Open/Closing` state machine with queued reopen (D3), NOT an AtomicBool guard |
| R10 | Focus-lost close races with hotkey toggle | Both paths funnel through the same `palette_close` Tauri command, which is idempotent in `Open` state and a no-op in `Closing` or `Closed` (D3) |
| R11 | `RenameCurrentMeeting` corrupts user files with folded scalars, anchors, aliases, literal blocks | **Fail-closed** per codex P1: parse via serde_yaml, require title is a plain-string scalar. Any non-trivial YAML → error, file unchanged. Parse-after-write validation restores backup on failure. See D8 test list |
| R12 | Rename collision: new title produces an existing slug | Reuse `markdown::resolve_collision`. The renamed file gets the next free suffix. Document in the confirmation toast |
| R13 | `ActionResponse` outer-typed but inner-untyped — overselling | Honest naming: "tagged envelope", not "typed". D7 lists exactly what it does and does not catch. Inner DTO typing is explicit follow-up |
| R14 | InputKind UI state machine is under-specified | Explicit reducer with (state, action) → state transitions in D9. ≥8 reducer tests. No "shortcut syntax" (`> search foo`) in slice 2 — select-then-type only |
| R15 | `current_meeting` source not defined for the overlay window | New Tauri command `palette_current_meeting` reads `CURRENT_MEETING.md` from the assistant workspace. Called by frontend before `palette_list` / `palette_execute`. Landed in 2a, not deferred |
| R16 | Dev-app TCC prompts block testing | Per CLAUDE.md, always use `./scripts/install-dev-app.sh` and test `~/Applications/Minutes Dev.app`. Export `MINUTES_DEV_SIGNING_IDENTITY` first for stable TCC. No testing against `/Applications/Minutes.app` |
| R17 | `ReprocessCurrentMeeting` deferred looks like scope cowardice | Codex pushed back legitimately. Reframe: cut for prioritization (slice 2 is already large), not hard blockage. Narrow version ("reprocess to sibling file") is a real option. Follow-up issue filed before slice 2 merges |
| R18 | PromptText modal state leaks into the command-list query on Esc | Reducer-level test in D9: LOCKED + Esc → BROWSING with **empty** query. Deterministic, not manual |
| R19 | The palette open latency target (<50 ms) is blown by Rust-side work on `palette_list` | `palette_list` iterates an 18-entry vector → nanoseconds. Any latency comes from window creation. If creation >50 ms, pre-create at app startup, hidden, and show on hotkey (v2.1 polish, not slice 2) |

